{{Infobox Galaxy | name = A2744_YD4 | image = Artist’s impression of the remote dusty galaxy A2744 YD4.jpg | caption = This artist’s impression shows what A2744_YD4 might look like.<ref>{{cite web|title=Artist’s impression of the remote dusty galaxy A2744_YD4|url=https://www.eso.org/public/images/eso1708a/|website=www.eso.org|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref> | epoch = [[J2000]] | constellation name = [[Sculptor (constellation)|Sculptor]] | ra = {{RA|00|14|24.927}}<ref name=Zheng>{{Cite journal|title=Young Galaxy Candidates in the Hubble Frontier Fields. I. Abell 2744|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=795|pages=93|author1=Zheng, W.|display-authors=etal |date=2014|arxiv=1402.6743|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/795/1/93|bibcode=2014ApJ...795...93Z|url=https://digital.csic.es/bitstream/10261/110433/1/I.%20A2744.pdf}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-30|22|56.15}}<ref name=Zheng/> | z = 8.38 <ref name=Laporte> Laporte, N.; Ellis, R. S.; Boone, F.; Bauer, F. E.; Quénard, D.; Roberts-Borsani, G. W.; Pelló, R.; Pérez-Fournon, I.; Streblyanska, A., ApJ, 2017, 837L, 21 </ref> | dist_ly = 13.2 billion ly (light-travel distance) | type = | appmag_v = | size_v = | notes = | names = [ZSM2014] YD4 }}
'''A2744_YD4''' is a very distant young [[galaxy]]. This galaxy has first been identified as a possible distant galaxy in 2015 using [[Hubble]]. This detection was made possible because this galaxy lies behind the massive galaxy cluster [[Abell 2744]]. In 2017, [[Atacama Large Millimeter Array|ALMA]] observed it and detected a small quantity of dust (the most distant stardust to date) and the first signature of Oxygen emitting light only 600 million years after the Big Bang <ref>{{cite web|title=Ancient Stardust Sheds Light on the First Stars - Most distant object ever observed by ALMA|url=https://www.eso.org/public/news/eso1708/|website=www.eso.org|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>.
