{{refimprove|date=October 2018}}

'''PyQuante''' is an open-source ([[BSD]]) suite of programs for developing quantum chemistry methods using [[Gaussian orbital|Gaussian type orbital (GTO)]] [[Basis set (chemistry)|basis sets]]. The program is written in the [[Python (programming language)|Python]] programming language, but has "rate-determining" modules written in [[C (programming language)|C]] for speed, and also uses and requires the [[NumPy]] linear algebra extensions to Python. The resulting code, though not as fast as other quantum chemistry programs, is much easier to understand and modify. The goal of this software is not necessarily to provide a working quantum chemistry program but rather to provide a set of tools so that scientists can construct their own quantum chemistry programs without going through the tedium of having to write every low-level routine.

==PyQuante features==
* [[Hartree&ndash;Fock]]: restricted closed-shell and [[Unrestricted Hartree–Fock|unrestricted]] open-shell implementations;
* [[Density functional theory]]: [[Local-density approximation|LDA]] (SVWN, Xalpha) and [[Generalized gradient approximation|GGA]] (BLYP) functionals;
* [[Optimized-effective potential]] method for orbital-dependent density functional approximations;
* Two electron integrals computed using Huzinaga, Rys, or [[Martin Head-Gordon|Head-Gordon]]/[[John Pople|Pople]] techniques; [[C (programming language)|C]] and [[Python (programming language)|Python]] interfaces to these programs;
* [[MINDO]]/3 [[semiempirical]] energies and forces;
* [[Configuration interaction|CI]]-singles excited states;
* [[DIIS]] convergence acceleration;
* Second-order [[Møller–Plesset perturbation theory]] (MP2).

==See also==
* [http://pyquante.sourceforge.net PyQuante SourceForge Site], which contains information and download links.
*PyQuante is written and maintained by [http://www.cs.sandia.gov/~rmuller Rick Muller].
